8 “SECTION 8. ORS 171.858 and 171.861 are repealed.
9 “SECTION 9. ORS 184.649 is amended to read:
10 “184.649. The Oregon Transportation Commission shall report on audits of the Department of
11 Transportation to the Joint Legislative Audit Committee established by ORS 171.580 and to [the
12 Joint Committee on Transportation established by ORS 171.858] the committees or interim com-
13 mittees of the Legislative Assembly related to transportation, at least once each biennium.
14 “SECTION 10. ORS 184.657 is amended to read:
15 “184.657. (1) The Oregon Transportation Commission shall develop a set of uniform standards,
16 in coordination with counties and cities, for the consistent description and reporting of the condition
17 of the transportation infrastructure owned by the state, counties and cities. The infrastructure de-
18 scribed must include pavement and bridges.
19 “(2) By February 1 of each odd-numbered year, every city and county shall submit a report
20 covering the condition of its transportation infrastructure.
21 “(3) The commission shall periodically review the condition of the transportation infrastructure
22 owned by the state and the reports submitted under this section. The commission shall post the re-
23 ports and the commission’s review of the reports on the website described in ORS 184.661.
24 “(4) Notwithstanding ORS 366.762 to 366.768 or 366.785 to 366.820, any city or county failing to
25 file a report under this section may not receive any payments from the State Highway Fund until
26 the report is filed.
27 “(5) Not later than June 1 of each odd-numbered year, the commission shall submit a report
28 about the state of the transportation infrastructure of Oregon, including the transportation
29 infrastructure of cities and counties, to:
30 “(a) The Legislative Assembly in the manner provided by ORS 192.245; and
31 “[(b) The Joint Committee on Transportation established under ORS 171.858.]
32 “(b) The committees or interim committees of the Legislative Assembly related to
33 transportation.
34 “SECTION 11. ORS 184.665, as amended by section 5, chapter 1, Oregon Laws 2025 (special
35 session), is amended to read:
36 “184.665. (1) As used in this section:
37 “(a) ‘Chief engineer’ means the person appointed by the Director of Transportation under ORS
38 184.628.
39 “(b) ‘Major project’ means a transportation project that costs $250 million or more to complete.
40 “(2) The Oregon Transportation Commission shall appoint a Continuous Improvement Advisory
41 Committee. The members of the committee shall include, but are not limited to, the following:
42 “(a) Members of the commission;
43 “(b) The Director of Transportation;
44 “(c) The chief engineer;
45 “(d) Individuals with demonstrated expertise in planning, executing and delivering major
SA to SB 1544 Page 2

1 projects; and
2 “(e) At least one individual with demonstrated knowledge and experience in the application and
3 implementation of the National Environmental Policy Act.
4 “(3) The committee shall:
5 “(a) Advise the commission on ways to maximize the efficiency of the Department of Transpor-
6 tation to allow increased investment in the transportation system over the short, medium and long
7 term.
8 “(b) Develop key performance measures, based on desired outcomes, for each division of the
9 department. The committee shall submit key performance measures to the commission for its ap-
10 proval. The committee shall report quarterly to the commission and to the [Joint Committee on
11 Transportation] committees or interim committees of the Legislative Assembly related to
12 transportation on the status of key performance measures and what steps are being taken by the
13 department to achieve the goals of the key performance measures.
14 “(4) The Continuous Improvement Advisory Committee shall report quarterly to the commission
15 and to the [Joint Committee on Transportation] committees or interim committees of the Legis-
16 lative Assembly related to transportation. The reports must include recommendations on ways
17 the commission and the department may execute their duties more efficiently.
18 “(5) The Continuous Improvement Advisory Committee shall meet at least once a month, at
19 times and places fixed by the chairperson of the committee or a majority of members of the com-
20 mittee.
21 “(6) The department shall provide office space and personnel to assist the committee as re-
22 quested by the chairperson, within the limits of available funds.
23 “(7) Members of the committee are entitled to compensation and expenses as provided under
24 ORS 292.495.
25 “SECTION 12. Section 1, chapter 323, Oregon Laws 2023, is amended to read:
26 “Sec. 1. (1) The Jurisdictional Transfer Advisory Committee is established within the Depart-
27 ment of Transportation.
28 “(2) The committee consists of 11 members appointed by the Governor. The members of the
29 committee shall include:
30 “(a) Two members who are transportation engineers;
31 “(b) Two members who represent cities and who have experience working on transportation
32 projects;
33 “(c) One member who represents a county and who has experience working on transportation
34 projects;
35 “(d) One member who represents a regional government and who has experience working on
36 transportation projects;
37 “(e) One member who represents road users;
38 “(f) One member who represents law enforcement;
39 “(g) One member who represents transit users;
40 “(h) One member who represents the advisory committee on bicycle traffic established in ORS
41 366.112; and
42 “(i) One member who represents the Transportation Safety Committee established in ORS
43 802.300.
44 “(3) The Governor shall appoint members to the Jurisdictional Transfer Advisory Committee so
45 that there is at least one member of the committee from each congressional district in this state.
SA to SB 1544 Page 3

1 “(4) The Jurisdictional Transfer Advisory Committee shall, from the jurisdictional transfer ap-
2 plications submitted under section 3 of this 2023 Act:
3 “(a) Review the applications; and
4 “(b) Develop a list of three jurisdictional transfers to recommend for funding.
5 “(5) The committee shall actively solicit reviews and comments from the Oregon Transportation
6 Commission in the development of the list described in subsection (4)(b) of this section. The com-
7 mittee shall also shall take into consideration the following:
8 “(a) The difference between the applicant’s and the department’s standards of maintenance;
9 “(b) The amount of deferred maintenance;
10 “(c) A description of how the highway is used in the community;
11 “(d) The climate impact of a transfer and subsequent upgrades the applicant could provide;
12 “(e) The potential positive impacts on historically underserved groups;
13 “(f) The increase in multimodal transportation options provided by a transfer;
14 “(g) A description of the safety issues that exist; and
15 “(h) A transfer readiness assessment that may include:
16 “(A) The interest of the community;
17 “(B) Funding capacity of the applicant for the transfer and maintenance in the future; and
18 “(C) The existing condition of the highway and its current state of maintenance.
19 “(6) No later than September 15 of each even-numbered year, the Jurisdictional Transfer Advi-
20 sory Committee shall submit a report to the [Joint Committee on Transportation] committees or
21 interim committees of the Legislative Assembly related to transportation, in the manner pro-
22 vided in ORS 192.245, that includes the list of jurisdictional transfers recommended for funding un-
23 der subsection (4)(b) of this section.
24 “(7) The term of office of each member of the Jurisdictional Transfer Advisory Committee is four
25 years, but a member serves at the pleasure of the Governor. Before the expiration of the term of a
26 member, the Governor shall appoint a successor whose term begins on January 1 next following. A
27 member is eligible for reappointment. However, a member of the committee may not serve more than
28 two terms. If there is a vacancy for any cause, the Governor shall make an appointment to become
29 immediately effective for the unexpired term. When a vacancy occurs in an appointment made from
30 a congressional district, the successor shall be appointed from the congressional district for which
31 the vacancy exists.
32 “(8) A majority of the members of the committee constitutes a quorum for the transaction of
33 business.
34 “(9) Official action by the committee requires the approval of a majority of the members of the
35 committee.
36 “(10) The committee shall elect one of its members to serve as chairperson.
37 “(11) The committee shall meet at times and places specified by the call of the chairperson or
38 of a majority of the members of the committee, provided that the committee meets at least four times
39 a year.
40 “(12) The committee may adopt rules necessary for the operation of the committee.
41 “(13) The Department of Transportation shall provide assistance and space for meetings as re-
42 quested by the chair of the committee.
43 “(14) Qualified members, as defined in ORS 292.495, of the advisory committee are entitled to
44 compensation for actual and necessary travel or other expenses incurred in the performance of their
45 official duties as specified for qualified members of boards or commissions in ORS 292.495 (4).
