1 “SECTION 13. Section 3, chapter 323, Oregon Laws 2023, is amended to read:
2 “Sec. 3. (1) The Department of Transportation shall adopt rules specifying the process by which
3 a city or county may apply for inclusion on the list of jurisdictional transfers recommended for
4 funding and submitted to the [Joint Committee on Transportation] committees or interim com-
5 mittees of the Legislative Assembly related to transportation under section 1 [of this 2023
6 Act], chapter 323, Oregon Laws 2023.
7 “(2) An application under this section must be on a form prescribed by the department and must
8 include the following:
9 “(a) The name of the city or county;
10 “(b) A description of the portion of the highway to be transferred;
11 “(c) A desired timeline for the transfer;
12 “(d) The scope of the transfer;
13 “(e) A description of which body assumes liability during and after the transfer;
14 “(f) The cost to update the segment of highway transferred to a state of good repair; and
15 “(g) Any other information necessary or helpful to the Jurisdictional Transfer Advisory Com-
16 mittee established in section 1 [of this 2023 Act], chapter 323, Oregon Laws 2023, in making its
17 recommendations to the [Joint Committee on Transportation] committees or interim committees
18 of the Legislative Assembly related to transportation.
19 “(3) A jurisdictional transfer applicant must submit:
20 “(a) Plans to provide at least 20 percent of the moneys required for the jurisdictional transfer;
21 and
22 “(b) A community vision plan that describes the applicant’s plan for managing and improving the
23 highway.
24 “SECTION 14. ORS 366.506, as amended by section 11, chapter 1, Oregon Laws 2025 (special
25 session), is amended to read:
26 “366.506. (1) Once every two years, the Oregon Department of Administrative Services shall
27 conduct a highway cost allocation study. The purpose of the study is to determine:
28 “(a) The proportionate share that the users of each class of vehicle should pay for the costs of
29 maintenance, operation and improvement of the highways, roads and streets in the state; and
30 “(b) Whether the users of each class are paying that share.
31 “(2) Each study must include:
32 “(a) An examination of the most recent study period for which actual data are available for the
33 purpose of determining the accuracy of the most recently published study results; and
34 “(b) An examination of the prospective study period based on projected data for the purpose
35 described in subsection (1) of this section that incorporates the results of the examination described
36 in paragraph (a) of this subsection.
37 “(3) The department may use any study design the department determines will best accomplish
38 the purposes stated in subsection (1) of this section. In designing the study, the department may
39 make decisions that include, but are not limited to, the methodology to be used for the study, what
40 constitutes a class of vehicle for purposes of collection of data under subsections (1) to (5) of this
41 section and the nature and scope of costs that will be included in the study.
42 “(4) The department may appoint a study review team to participate in the study required by
43 subsection (1) of this section. The team may perform any functions assigned by the department, in-
44 cluding, but not limited to, consulting on the design of the study.
45 “(5) A report on the results of the study shall be submitted to the legislative revenue committees
