18 “SECTION 19. Section 8, chapter 1, Oregon Laws 2025 (special session), is amended to read:
19 “Sec. 8. (1) As used in this section, ‘highway improvement project’ means a state highway
20 project for which the Department of Transportation may use federal transportation funds.
21 “(2) If a city or county proposes to expand the scope of a highway improvement project, but does
22 not provide funding, the city or county shall submit the proposed change to the Oregon Transpor-
23 tation Commission. If the commission approves the proposed change, the commission shall submit a
24 report to the [Joint Committee on Transportation] committees or interim committees of the
25 Legislative Assembly related to transportation that informs the committee about the proposed
26 change and cost associated with the expanded scope. After reviewing the report, the committee may
27 submit recommendations for appropriations that may be made in the future to cover the costs of the
28 expanded scope of the highway improvement project.
29 “(3) This section applies to highway improvement projects when a city or county is not covering
30 the costs of the expanded scope and:
31 “(a) The project costs less than $25 million and the changes in scope the city or county is re-
32 questing increase the project costs by 10 percent or more; or
33 “(b) The project costs $25 million or more and the changes in scope the city or county is re-
34 questing increase the project costs by five percent or more.
35 “SECTION 20. Section 14, chapter 1, Oregon Laws 2025 (special session), is amended to read:
36 “Sec. 14. (1) In consultation with the study review team described in ORS 366.506, the Oregon
37 Department of Administrative Services shall undertake a review of the methodology for the highway
38 cost allocation study required under ORS 366.506.
39 “(2) The department shall examine all aspects of the methodology for the highway cost allo-
40 cation study, including but not limited to the following:
41 “(a) The revenues and expenditures included in the highway cost allocation study;
42 “(b) How costs are allocated across different classes of vehicles;
43 “(c) What constitutes a class of vehicle;
44 “(d) The data used in the highway cost allocation study;
45 “(e) The level of granularity to which cost responsibility is calculated for potential rate changes;
